From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: ci <ci@local>
Date: Sun, 24 May 2026 00:10:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ask: suppress PR14z18 auto-unbind to protect FMan-shared
 management plane (PR14z23.1)

PR14z18 fired ask_hw_port_unbind() automatically whenever a pipeline's
per-pipeline live-cookie refcount transitioned to zero (last
FLOW_CLS_DESTROY on the test plane).  ask_hw_port_unbind() calls
fman_pcd_kg_ungraft_cc() which rewrites the KeyGen scheme through the
*shared* FMan indirect-access window (AR-flushed), serializing the
entire FMan's parse → classify pipeline for the duration of the RMW.

On Mono Gateway DK, that stall is observable as ARP/keepalive loss on
the management LAN (eth0/eth1/eth2 RJ45 ports on 192.168.0.0/16 —
FMan MAC5/MAC6/MAC2) every time a flow_offload cookie storm drains
the per-pipeline refcount to zero on the SFP+ test-plane ports
(eth3/eth4 on /30 link nets — FMan MAC9/MAC10).  Confirmed via ftrace
on the live DUT 2026-05-24: two ask_hw_port_unbind() calls per M2
gate run (port 0x10 + 0x11) correlate 1:1 with operator-reported
management-network disruption.

This is a production safety bug: any legitimate flowtable teardown
(operator removes a port from `set vpp settings interface`, SFP+ link
flap, `nft delete table inet ask_offload`) will brown out the mgmt
plane for the same reason.

Fix: keep the per-pipeline refcount + the log line (so the next-step
investigation of "who queues the destroy work bypassing
flow_offload_queue_work" can resume safely once the FMan-wide stall is
removed), but DO NOT invoke ask_hw_port_unbind() from the destroy
path.  Leaving cc_v4_tcp grafted across a cookie storm is safe:
silicon HIT keeps forwarding the 5-tuples already in the CC table,
and the next REPLACE burst (typically <2 s later under sustained TCP
load) re-populates the same tree.  The kernel-side cookies being
destroyed are bookkeeping records, not silicon entries.  cc_v4_tcp
trees are still torn down properly via ask_hw_pcd_teardown() on
module exit and on flavour reconfiguration — the only legitimate
ungraft points until a future patch introduces a proper
flowtable-gone signal (FLOW_BLOCK_UNBIND is documented as never fired
by the kernel 6.18.31 nftables flowtable lifecycle on `nft delete
table`, per PR14z18 design comment).

See plans/PR14z23-DESIGN.md "## 2026-05-24 00:05Z — ftrace IDENTIFIES
destroy caller + CRITICAL management-network disruption" for the
ftrace evidence and the root-cause analysis.

Signed-off-by: ASK2 build bot <ask2-build@kralj.dev>
---
diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/ask/ask_hw.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/ask/ask_hw.c
index dc41947..e5ab323 100644
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/ask/ask_hw.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/freescale/dpaa/ask/ask_hw.c
@@ -1502,9 +1502,40 @@ int ask_hw_flow_remove(u32 hw_flow_id)
                 mutex_unlock(&h->lock);
 
                 if (pid_to_unbind != 0xff) {
-                        ask_pr_info("hw: PR14z18 auto-unbind: port 0x%02x — last cookie destroyed, ungrafting\n",
+                        /*
+                         * PR14z23.1 (2026-05-24): SUPPRESS the actual
+                         * ungraft.  ask_hw_port_unbind() calls
+                         * fman_pcd_kg_ungraft_cc() which rewrites the
+                         * KeyGen scheme through the *shared* FMan
+                         * indirect-access window (AR-flushed),
+                         * serializing the entire FMan's parse →
+                         * classify pipeline for the duration.  That
+                         * stall is observable as ARP/keepalive loss
+                         * on the management LAN (eth0/1/2,
+                         * 192.168.0.0/16) every time a flow_offload
+                         * cookie storm drains the per-pipeline
+                         * refcount to zero on the test-plane SFP+
+                         * ports (eth3/eth4).
+                         *
+                         * Leaving cc_v4_tcp grafted across a cookie
+                         * storm is safe: silicon HIT keeps forwarding
+                         * the 5-tuples already in the CC table, and
+                         * the next REPLACE burst (typically <2 s
+                         * later under sustained TCP load) re-populates
+                         * the same tree.  The kernel-side cookies
+                         * being destroyed are bookkeeping records,
+                         * not silicon entries.
+                         *
+                         * The cc_v4_tcp trees are torn down properly
+                         * via ask_hw_pcd_teardown() on module exit
+                         * (rmmod ask) and on flavour reconfiguration,
+                         * which are the only legitimate ungraft
+                         * points until a future patch introduces a
+                         * proper flowtable-gone signal.
+                         */
+                        ask_pr_info("hw: PR14z23.1: skip auto-unbind on port 0x%02x — last cookie destroyed but cc_v4_tcp left grafted (FMan-wide stall avoidance)\n",
                                     pid_to_unbind);
-                        (void)ask_hw_port_unbind(pid_to_unbind);
+                        /* (void)ask_hw_port_unbind(pid_to_unbind); -- SUPPRESSED, see comment */
                 }
         }
         return 0;
